I haven't checked whether your statement about colliding fusion pellets is true, but I worked the numbers you requested.<br>
<br>
===============================<br>
<br>
Part one: Energy required to move pellet<br>
------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
Kinetic Energy = 1/2 x Mass X (Velocity squared)   (or 0.5 mv^2)<br>
<br>
Velocity required = 200,000 meters per second  (or m/s) <br>
Assume a 1 gram pellet<br>
<br>
So...<br>
<br>
KE = 0.5 x .001kilograms x 200,000m/s ^2<br>
<br>
KE = 0.5 x .001 x 40,000,000,000 <br>
<br>
so...<br>
KE = 20,000,000 joules are required<br>
======================================<br>
<br>
<br>
Part two: Quantity of anti-protons to supply energy<br>
<br>
------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
Energy of proton-antiproton annihilation ~<br>
 0.000000000131 joules<br>
This does not include the kinetic energy of the escaping neutrinos - no way are you going to capture that!<br>
<br>
Since you require 20,000,000 joules...<br>
<br>
Antiprotons required = 2 x 10^7 / 1.31 x 10^-10<br>
or roughly 150,000,000,000,000,000 antiprotons<br>
<br>
------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
This assumes 100 percent efficiency in transferring the energy to the pellet. I would guess that &lt;&lt; 10% would be much more likely. So multiply the number by 10 or whatever you wish to use.<br>
<br>
(double check if I slipped some decimal points. I do that all the time)<br>
